segments.text: One, two, three, four, one, two.
One, two, three, four, one, two, three, four, one, two.
One, two, three, four, one, two, three.
This is August 25.
We're in the Blocker Building, and I have the pleasure and honor of chatting with Carl Schaefer, professor of agricultural economics and a friend for almost 40 years.

For the sake of someone, Carl, who might not know you when they listen to this tape or read the transcript a half century from now, describe your family background, growing up, where you went to school, college, graduate school, and so forth.
No worries.
Describe Carl Schaefer before getting to College Station.
From birth?
Yes.
I was born in Oklahoma City.
the depth of the Depression.
Moved to Alva, Oklahoma in 1934.
My father's health was such that he couldn't continue to work in the hotel, so he came to Alva, Oklahoma, the home of my grandparents, my grandfather having come here from Germany in, we think, 1877.
Alva's a wheat farming community in northwest Oklahoma.
My father moved into the back of my grandfather's harness shop with a radio shop, which I always thought was an interesting juxtaposition.
Buggies and cornice in the front and radios in the back.
I grew up in Alva, Oklahoma.
Should I mention the gold bugs and the green bugs?
Where are our mascots?
Went to Alva High School and I went to Oklahoma A&M College.
It was then in Stillwater, Oklahoma, which became in 1957 Oklahoma State University as we know it.

I got a BS degree, and actually I played basketball there, but I had to take something, so I took agricultural economics for BS, and I got a master's of agricultural economics while I was waiting around for my wife to graduate, and although I was interested in the field.
We left there in 57, went into the Army.
The Army had a surplus of officers, so I only did six months active duty for training at Fort Monmouth, New Jersey.
And then from there we went to graduate school at Pennsylvania State University.
From fall of 1957 when Sputnik went up and a lot of money was then thrown at higher education institutions, agriculture being among the recipients.
And as the Penn State left there in 1961, I actually came to my first job and only job academically was at Texas A&M University from January of 62.
through September of 1998.
We arrived here on one of the coldest days of the year, January 62.
The place was frozen.
That's a very quick summary of where we've been.
How did you and A&M link up?
What were they looking for, and how did they find you, and how did you find them?
Well, I had met, people didn't visit, in those days you didn't go somewhere, at least I didn't go somewhere for an interview.
You sort of did things over the phone, by word of mouth, by somebody else that was known.
I had actually interviewed with Texas A&M at the summer meetings, which are the big meetings of the American Agricultural Economic Association in 1960.
Ty Timm and John McNeely were there, Bob Branson, and I interviewed with them, but I didn't have the job, I think, probably until we got to be 1961.

Then a friend of mine who'd been at Penn State, C. Harold Brown, and his wife Sally were here in sociology because the department was the Department of Agricultural Economics and Sociology, not rural sociology, but sociology.
And so Hal seemed to like it here, so we thought it sounded good, and we were also provincial because it was close to home.
Being from Oklahoma, we wanted to get somewhere back in the territory.
We had two children, and of course we had two sets of grandparents in Oklahoma,
But I had never heard of Texas A&M until I was a senior in high school and went to a football game at Oklahoma University.
They were playing Texas A&M, and there was all these people standing over in the Texas A&M section, which I thought was really strange.
They were all in uniform, and that's really the first time that I'd ever heard of Texas A&M, as I said, being provincial.
But we got here through the fact that it was located where it was and through Hal and Sally Brown, and I think at that time A&M was breaking out of its
somewhat narrow orientation in terms of whom they were hiring.
When I got here, there were, gosh, almost everybody in our department had their degrees from Texas A&M.
And I think I was the third, maybe the third or fourth guy in the department who didn't have their degree, their terminal degree, as we say, from Texas A&M.
Did you interview over the phone?
Was there a kind of an interview, or back in the summer?
Yeah, there was a, well, at Colorado State, which is where the meetings were in the 60s,
I had talked to Branson and Tim and Neely, but I did not come down here.
No, I'd never been here.
But did they interview you?
Yes, yes, we talked, we visited.
I mean, it wasn't really a very formal interview, but we did visit.
As you recall, what were their key concerns about whomever they might be hiring?
Oh, gosh, that's been a while, Haskell.
Branson was really looking for somebody to work with him in what would become the Market Research Center.
And I was in marketing.
I had been in milk marketing.
I'd done my work in the Amish country up there on bulk milk handling.
But it was close enough to marketing that they were interested in someone in marketing.
And that's about as far as we got, I think.
Who else they talked about?
The people at Oklahoma State they may have interviewed.
I don't know.
And of course, the head at Penn State.
But I can't remember other than just wanting to get somebody in marketing and somebody with a degree other than.
Do you remember what kind of paperwork you submitted to them as a part of the review process?
Well, it wasn't very extensive.
I'm sure there was probably a letter.
I remember what I filled out when I got here, some of that, but the job application wasn't very complicated.
As far as you know, did they make some phone calls to some of your former teachers?
You know, I had to provide references, and I assume they did, but I really don't know.
part of my career weakness was that I didn't ever seek much advice from people or discuss with them as much as I should with them, I think, but I imagine they did.
I know when we got here, we had to sign a loyalty oath.
I remember that.
It was a page that must have been hundreds of organizations.
I remember that piece of paper worked.
But other than that, it seemed pretty standard stuff.
When you came, how long did you assume you might be here?
Well, you know, in that day, in the 60s, the early 60s,
the mark of a good academic was that you moved a lot.
I mean, people were coming.
You remember Russ Thompson was here.
And of course, Hal left six months after we got here, Hal Brown did.
And so you moved a lot if you were that active.
I've always been sort of a static equilibrium person.
I'm not that interested in moving, but more in doing the career where I was.
So I don't know, I guess you thought
If I ever thought about it, maybe, you know, five or ten years, first job, not necessarily stay here, but Texas A&M began to change so much.
Did you have any school that hidden back in your mind was your ultimate, ultimate goal?
No, I interviewed at Ohio State, but that was an extension position.
I wasn't interested in that.
But as far as going back to Oklahoma State, no, that wasn't particularly an objective.
I think I was happy, as happy at A&M as I probably would have been most places.
Maybe somebody thinks about, no, I don't think I want to go to Harvard.
Did any of your Penn State faculty or student colleagues tell you anything about A&M?
What was their impression of A&M?
Okay, we had a faculty member at Penn State, Larry Foraker, Professor Foraker in economics.
His father had been on the faculty in engineering at Texas A&M, and I think his family was still here when I got here.
Foraker went on to be dean of the business school at Harvard, which was interesting because he graduated a Ph.D. from Colorado.
But he was a very good, I guess a very good administrator.
He was a good academician.
And I talked to Dr. Foraker about coming to A&M.
And as I recall, he said, well, it's a good place to start.
That was about the only advice he had.
And I always saw him a few times afterward.
But other than that, I don't think most of the guys at Penn State knew much about Texas A&M.
Did anybody tell you anything about College Station O'Brien before you got here?
Not a bit.
Not a bit.
Didn't know what we were getting into.
As I said, we drove in.
It was freezing, freezing.
Describe what you and your wife and children brought with you.
How voluminous were your belongings?
We had a two-wheel U-Haul trailer, orange and white, I remember, which we packed in Pennsylvania, and one of the pieces was a dry sink, an antique dry sink from...
Pennsylvania, which if we'd known better, we'd have thrown all our furniture away, loaded with antiques and brought them down here because they were more valuable in Texas.
But we got all of our stuff in a two-wheel U-Haul trailer, which we reloaded in Oklahoma City because we could save money by switching trailers in Oklahoma City to come to Texas.
But that was it.
We slid all the way from Penn State, from State College down through
Well, all the way down here, it was icy and snowy.
I remember that.
But it was a risky trip.
But we didn't take much to have our possessions.
And describe what it was like to find a place to live.
Well, now we had, I keep forgetting people, but we knew, we also knew some guys who were at Penn State.
They had a big meteorology Air Force program.
And one of them was, I can't think of Andy's last name, but Andy had been
come to Texas A&M.
He's from Tennessee.
He was on the faculty here in mechanical engineering.
I forgot.
I just remembered this just now.
And Andy and Wanda had found us a house over on Nagel, $90 a month.
And it was a two-bedroom, a very nice house, not far from the campus.
So we had already picked out for us a house.
We were lucky.
We were lucky these kids had got it for us.
And, of course, Hal and Sally were here, too.
But you hadn't seen it yet.
No, no, I hadn't seen it.
No, no.
No, we hadn't seen the house.
We just pulled in sight unseen.
Describe what it was like to become a part of the neighborhood and a part of the community for you and Peggy and the children.
Well, our idea in becoming a part of the neighborhood was mostly to join a church, to find a church.
And we visited around.
We had been Southern Baptists all our lives.
Then we got to Pennsylvania and we became American Baptists.
And then we came back down here, we visited around, and finally found the, located at First Baptist Church College Station.
That really became our locus of our community.
The neighborhood, Zerl Carpenter, who became director of extension, lived about four blocks down from me when he first moved in from Wisconsin as an assistant professor in animal science.
I'm trying to remember who else lived on Nagel Street.
A few other prominent people lived there.
My next door neighbor was a milkman, Albert Gruss, and electrical engineering was next door.
But we only lived there, we were there about four years, I guess, before we moved over to Gilchrist.
So we did meet some of the neighbors, but mostly our social stuff, you know, was the department and the church.
That's where we were from.
All right, describe...
I've got a frog in my throat.
Okay, describe your first days, weeks, months in the department.
getting received, an office, and getting acquainted, and undertaking your first work?
Okay, we're in the agriculture building, renamed the history building, right in front of what used to be, well, no, no, it wasn't in front of then.
It was between the systems building and the library, which was only a single building, Cushing.
So we're running between the Texas engineering station and the system building.
But the ag building consisted of agriculture economics, poultry science, and weed science, whatever that is, was in the basement.
My office was with two other faculty in room 300 of the agriculture building, top floor.
There were three of us in there shortly, and I got another office.
But I remember moving up there in January, and it was cold.
I didn't teach the first semester because that was springtime, just showed up.
I missed the first, I missed the Agricultural Primer Station Conference by a few days.
I know Ty wasn't happy about that.
He thought I should be there for that, which I didn't know was happening.
But I haven't met him, and I forget the other person that was up there in that room.
So I started teaching, I think, the next fall.
In agriculture, we didn't teach like you do in history.
We don't teach as many courses.
We're about half research, half teaching.
And then the summer came.
But I got oriented.
I went around, met the dean.
I didn't meet President Rutter until he had come over to Dr. Tim's office later.
I met him, but I didn't meet.
I showed you around the dean.
I met the director of Experiment Station.
Try and think who that... Oh, gosh.
He was a guy from Penn State.
Lewis?
Yeah, R.D.
Lewis, yeah.
Great old gentleman.
What was your initial impression of the dean and of Dr. Lewis?
Well, the dean was...
from Louisiana.
Gus Watkins?
No, no.
Patterson?
Patterson, yeah.
R.E.
Patterson.
And he had played basketball.
Since I had played basketball.
We hit it off very well.
But, you know, what did I know?
I was like a fish in...
He doesn't know he's wet.
I didn't know what administrators were supposed to be like.
I had only known professors by and large.
Everybody seemed very pleasant.
It was a very cordial place.
We felt welcome.
I know Ty and Valerie and... Who was the guy in the English department?
Johnny...
A friend of Ty's, first month we were here, they took us to Houston and took us shopping.
John Paul Abbott?
No, it wasn't John.
This guy was Johnny.
He was from East Texas.
His wife was a Cajun.
I can't think of his last name.
He was in the English department, not John Paul Abbott.
Anyhow, these people all seemed, you know, like good folks to me.
I think one thing that impressed me was everybody had a title.
I wasn't used to leaders of this and directors of that.
Everybody I knew was just professor or doctor.
So I had to get used to the nomenclature.
But I thought we were well received.
What about Rudder when you first met?
What was your impression of him?
Very impressive.
It wasn't standoffish so much as austere.
I held him in great awe.
This was a man, and one didn't mess with him.
I didn't see a lot of his humor, but you paid attention when he spoke.
So he came to Dr. Tim's office.
In fact, as I recall, we were there
He said he didn't want to, and I think this conversation took place when we were in Dr. Tim's office about not integrating
the school with females and the Corps, making the Corps voluntary, but then he was saying that he was going to have to do this.
He was going to have to do this or the place was going to survive.
My memory says that I heard that in Dr. Tim's office.
I may be wrong, but I know he met in his office with President Rutter.
Was any mention made in that conversation about his academic background and or his link to agriculture, his interest in agriculture?
Well, it seemed, as I recall, he was interested in agriculture, but there was no mention of his academic background.
In fact, I didn't even know that he didn't have an extensive academic background for some time.
Now, did anybody in the department or outside of the department give you, as a new faculty member, advice on how to behave, what to wear, what to do or not do?
Oh, yeah, very clear on what to wear.
You always wore a tie, and if you were going to teach, of course, you wore a coat and tie.
And even in the summertime, we would wear ties, short-sleeved shirts, no question about that, no shorts.
I mean, nobody caught, you know, you're always dressed with a tie and appropriate attire, long pants.
And in the summer, the first year I got here was the last year that the agricultural building was not air-conditioned.
Now, some of the guys had their own window units.
They belonged to them.
They were their own.
And at that
I think 63 then, they air conditioned the building.
But that summer of 62, and they showed me why.
People brought towels to the office, and they would lay the towel on their desk.
And you would write so that it would absorb the perspiration as you sat there in that office.
Now, you had a window, but still it was very hot if you didn't have an air conditioner.
And President Rutter, I think the rumor was, thought when they air conditioned the building, he was going to get these units.
He didn't realize that they belonged to the faculty.
So they all disappeared.
and went back home or someplace.
In terms of appearance, what about haircuts, beards, and mustaches?
No, no beards.
Maybe there had been some mustaches, but no beards.
Everybody had short hair, at least that I knew.
Of course, agriculture was a little different, but even the rest of the colleges.
No, it was a very straight laced.
Did Dr. Tim or anybody else give you any advice about being a new faculty member and what to do to succeed?
You know, that's a good question.
I think you sort of knew what you... McNeely probably did more of that, John McNeely, than Dr. Tim.
And at that time, publication was desired, but it wasn't the ultimate good in life.
It was sort of a mixture of things, research and teaching in our case, some extension work, some service, they call it service work.
But they weren't heavy-handed with advice because you were given a little more...
I don't know if you call it freedom, but there wasn't as much, the pressure wasn't as great.
It was more academic in the old sense where you were more your own boss and did your own thing as long as you kept busy.
I probably didn't seek enough advice.
Was anything ever said about alcohol, tobacco, or anything like that?
I don't remember the alcohol thing, but tobacco.
Houston Smith, who was sort of an assistant, he was really a cowboy.
who Dr. Tim had brought in to do survey work and research for research data, Houston Smith would stand at the door of room 300 when it became a meeting room with a box of cigars.
And everybody almost would take a cigar when we went in for a faculty meeting.
And I mean, when the faculty meeting got started, it was blue.
You could hardly see anybody else in the room because everybody was smoking something.
But I remember that box of King Edward cigars he'd stand there with at the door.
And everybody, it was, you know, it would be a nightmare in today's world.
Who paid for them?
Who bought the cigars?
I have no idea.
Maybe Ty.
I'm sure Houston didn't.
Now, there's a good kind of thing to show how times have changed.
Oh, yeah.
About how often did the department meet?
Oh, gosh, I think we had a weekly staff conference.
We had too many.
I believe we met once a week.
And how many people would be there?
Everybody.
How many was that?
Oh.
The room full must have been 30, 45 people.
What kind of issues did you all discuss?
Well, a lot of things that probably didn't need discussing, but everything from, I suppose, the plumbing, I'm not sure what all.
Not many big decisions were discussed because Ty pretty much took care of those.
I think he'd bring things up that he was going to discuss, but I don't remember that it seemed like to us younger faculty members that we spent too much time in meetings.
So that's a good question.
What did we discuss?
They weren't seminars.
They were faculty meetings, mostly where you got information you were given.
And he was the department head, not the chairman.
For sure.
He was a benevolent department head, yes.
Can you give some examples of early, in the early years you were here, of the kinds of decisions that he made?
Well, I think all, as far as I can remember now, unlike the way it is now, then promotions and things like that were decided by probably Ty and John McNeely and Pat Wooten.
Pat Wooten, the department was set up so that Ty was the head, John McNeely ran the research side, Pat Wooten did the teaching side,
which included graduate and undergraduate at that time.
Later, they brought in J.C. Grady as the undergraduate guy, and Pat was the graduate advisor.
And I'm thinking, I may be wrong on this, it seems like Reagan Brown sort of handled the extension part, but I could be wrong on that.
But Ty had it pretty well organized, where he was the leader, and these other
divisions were headed up by other people.
And as far as you knew, he's the one that had made the decision to hire you.
Well, I'm sure he consulted with McNeely.
I think he was really close to McNeely and Pat Wooten.
And I'm sure the three of them would have to, particularly he and McNeely would agree on it.
As far as you could compare
At about the time you came here, compare agricultural economics at Penn State and at Texas A&M.

Well, at that time, Penn State would have been considerably, if you look at publications and quote, learned journals, unquote, and the reputation of their staff, Penn State would have been certainly above Texas A&M.
But that's what Texas A&M is working on, bringing in people like Russell Thompson.
And I can remember the guy who became quickly head of, or worked at a station down here, Jim.
My memory's failing me.
But I mean, they had good economists here, like C.A.
Bonin and people of that caliber.
But these guys, they didn't have PhDs.
But they did good, solid work.
Bonnen's son later became a fellow in the association, Jim Bonnen, up at Michigan State.
I'm sure I'm overlooking some people, but Penn State would have definitely been a higher rank than Texas A&M.
Tim was known, but if you looked at the journal articles at that time, you might find one by Ty.
They brought in Ken Tiefertiller, too, from Oklahoma.
A&M had come down here.
He was one of the other additions.
But it was definitely...
And southern departments were kind of looked down on in those days.
But Penn State would definitely have been above it in rank, and A&M would have been at that, I think.
All right.
Did you get the impression early that A&M was planning on moving up in quality and reputation?
Oh, yeah.

Yeah, that was pretty clear by the people that, the three people that were, three or four that were here before I got here in terms of spreading out the geographical distribution of degrees and that sort of thing.
Yeah, I don't think there was any question.
Even in early 62, they were
working toward that.
Now, your beginning salary was how much?
Seventy-five hundred dollars.
Twelve months?
Twelve months.
Twelve months.
And what was your original assignment, teaching, research, and so forth, what were you to do?
I'm guessing, and I may be wrong, but it was no more than twenty to twenty-five percent teaching and the rest of it was research.
And you have to remember that in those days
Agriculture got lots of money from the federal government through the Hatch Act, the marketing side.
I forget all the history on that, but we had no problem
no problem getting research money.
It was by formula, and it was allocated out to the states, and I could tell you some stories that I've heard from history professors on what they had versus what we had, but I won't go into that.
But so we had lots of research money, relatively speaking, and we didn't teach, nobody taught much in the way, maybe one course a year, maybe two courses a year max.
That's the way it was.
All right, and you were assigned to do what kind of research?
Marketing.
I did marketing research.
When I first got here, I know we did some carrot marketing.
And the Valley was having trouble with their carrot marketing order and getting low prices and lots of volatility and risk going on down there.
Got into grapefruit marketing, same sort of thing.
Got into some egg marketing in East Texas and so on.
Marketing projects, how do we improve the prices?
How do we improve the marketing system?
Much of it was descriptive research.
It was not journal based necessarily.
Who did you work with from the campus to get started in those assignments and what kind of contacts did you make out in the field?
Well we worked with, I worked mostly with Bob Branson at that time and making these contacts and other people in marketing
Some with Swede Sorenson.
I've forgotten Swede's first name because he was always Swede Sorenson.
He was into vegetables.
But in the Valley, we made contacts.
Most commodities have an association with Texas Grapefruit Producers, Texas Vegetable Growers Associations, and so on.
So we made contacts with them.
I remember when I first got here, first year or two, got a fantastic grant from the Texas Vegetable Growers.
I think it was like $2,000.
This was big bucks in those days.
So once we got out of association, we would work with them.
But most of our work, we didn't get grants.
They didn't support that because you had money from the federal government to do these studies.
And what about the county, the local county agents or regional extension officers?
Did you work with them much in those early years?
The research side, we would make contact with them, let them know we were there.
But generally, you operated
at least I did, in the marketing side, since it wasn't production economics, I was doing marketing, you operated somewhat independently of that.
They wanted to know if you were around, if you were in their territory.
Can you give some anecdotes that you remember about what it was like for an Oklahoman to get acquainted with some Texans out in the field?
How did a farmer respond to somebody that was there to help him?
Yeah, right.
The farmers were okay.
It was the next step up, the packers, the shippers, the guys who sometimes when you were studying them, and Oklahoma is not that much different from Texas.
I mean, Texas may not believe that, but it's not an altogether foreign country.

It was the proprietors, and I almost got in some trouble down in the valley because we were investigating the carrot thing, and it was our hypothesis and I think a fact that the shippers took advantage of the growers.
And looking into that, I was almost carried out of office one time bodily because that was none of our damn business.
And leave him alone, don't ever come back.
So the producers were sympathetic to what we were trying to do because mainly it was producer-based marketing.
But many times the middlemen, the next step up, the buyer, the packer, the shipper, were not sympathetic to what you were doing unless they had initiated the project.
I never had trouble with the Texas farmers, identifying with them, because I had come from a farming community.
I wasn't a farm boy, but I worked on a farm, wheat harvest and so on, when I was a kid.
So I felt comfortable with them.
Was this your first encounter with Hispanic farmers, workers?
Well, we didn't, I hadn't, I can't think of a thing where I, any occasions where I encountered
Hispanics.
The people I worked with in the valley, lower Grand Valley, were all Anglos.
And the workers or any farmers were Anglos.
The shippers were Anglos.
The workers, of course, out there were a lot of Hispanics, but I had no direct contact with them.
So there was not that, I didn't feel that influence, although I was right here in the middle of it.
All right.
In those early years, about how much time were you on the road?
How often were you out?
Well, we'd go out fairly often to gather data, whether it was with the Valley, of course.
That was always an overnight trip.
And you usually drove down there, and you'd stay, you know, two or three nights maybe.
And then if you went to Dallas to get data, you'd probably stay overnight with some... Well, you always stayed in a hotel or motel.
But I was on the road.
It's not like being in the extension service in Texas.
Now, there you spend your life on the road.
Even today, it's...
They spent a lot of time out, but I wasn't gone that much getting data, and we got primary data a lot of the time for research purposes, but I wasn't gone that much on the road.
And in what vehicle or vehicles did you go?
Well, you always used a departmental or a motor pool vehicle.
You could check them out.
You didn't take your own car, rarely did you, and you just checked it out of the motor pool.
Did you ever have any unusual problems with one of those vehicles?
Not that I remember.
I know we didn't take them anywhere that we weren't supposed to.
No, but I mean, one never broke down halfway between nowhere?
No, I never had any trouble with them.
We did have a departmental vehicle.
It was a Chevrolet, whatever that thing was that had the motor in the back.
And we used to have trouble with that.
But no, I don't remember being stranded with those vehicles.
They were in fairly good shape.
And then later on, you begin to take your own vehicle.
And you just got paid mileage.
But most of us in those days only had one car.
And so if you took your car, your wife had no car.
So you didn't do that.
Do you remember what the per diem was in those days?
No, I remember motels, though, were like, you know, less than $20.
And I really don't remember what the per diem was.
It wasn't much.
It didn't have to be much.
Did anybody give you any private advice of what?
